\section{The package will not install}{

\code{install_github} ends in compiler, \code{make}, or \verb{g++} errors rather than a
dflasso message. dflasso compiles a little C++ on install and no C++ toolchain
is present. Install a compiler first, then install dflasso. On Windows that is
Rtools, matched to the R major version, then restart R. On macOS it is the
Xcode command-line tools, \code{xcode-select --install}. On Linux it is
build-essential or the Development Tools group. Check with
\code{pkgbuild::check_build_tools()}. With no local toolchain, use the repository's
\code{Dockerfile}.
}

\section{It installed but library(dflasso) errors}{

The error is \verb{unable to load shared object}, or a missing-symbol crash on the first
call. The install is partial or corrupt, or it built without the compiler so
the compiled routines were never registered. Re-install with a working
compiler as above, confirm with \code{pkgbuild::check_build_tools()}, then
\code{install.packages(..., type = "source")} again.
}

\section{"No scenario has complete realised costs..."}{

\code{\link[=dfl_fit]{dfl_fit()}} stops. Zero instances are fully observed over the elements the
solver looks at, so decision quality cannot be scored. Because it is a
\code{stop()}, there is no fit object to inspect. Read the coverage report the
error prints; it ends "See the coverage report for which elements are
missing." The same report is on \code{prepare_instances(...)$coverage}. Then make a
handful of instances complete over their solve set by reconstructing the
per-element costs that were not captured; for routing, model-based travel
times or historical arc averages joined by arc and day. A custom solver that
provably inspects only a subset of rows can declare that subset with
\code{solve_support} on \code{\link[=optimization_problem]{optimization_problem()}}; this does nothing for the
built-ins, whose solve set is intrinsic. Raising \code{min_elements_per_scenario}
does not help; coverage tests completeness, which is separate.
}

\section{"Only N instances have complete cost data..."}{

A warning; the fit proceeds. Fully covered instances number between 1 and 30,
so the scores carry more sampling noise. The fix is more fully covered
instances (reconstruct per-element costs). Short of that, raise \code{n_splits} to
30 or 50 in \code{\link[=dfl_control]{dfl_control()}} to average over more resamples. Read the scores
cautiously: judge a feature by its \code{proxy_score} in \code{tidy(fit)} rather than
its label, and confirm direction with \code{\link[=regret]{regret()}}.
}

\section{"nfolds must be bigger than 3" or "only N scenarios have enough rows to fit"}{

dflasso stops with its own message before glmnet can throw the raw \verb{nfolds must be bigger than 3} error. The cause is too few usable scenarios after
filtering: dflasso models elements within a scenario, drops any scenario with
fewer than \code{min_elements_per_scenario} observed-cost rows, then
cross-validates across the survivors. A shape with one row per scenario leaves
nothing to fit. The fixes, in order: give more rows per scenario; for data
that really is one row per scenario set \code{min_elements_per_scenario = 1} in
\code{\link[=dfl_control]{dfl_control()}}; or lower \code{nfolds}. When fewer scenarios survive than the
requested \code{nfolds} but at least three remain, dflasso reduces the folds and
warns rather than stopping; raise the row count or lower \code{nfolds} to silence
that.
}

\section{The fit is very slow or looks hung}{

The decision-quality step runs \code{solve} about 5.5 times for every fully
covered instance, so many instances or a slow \code{solve} add up. By default an
interactive session prints one start line and a \code{Done.} for this step while a
script stays silent; change it with \code{progress} in \code{\link[=dfl_control]{dfl_control()}}. To speed it
up, move any cost-independent setup out of \code{solve} and into the \code{instance}
object (a prebuilt graph, matrix, or index) so each call does the minimum.
Then set \code{workers = parallel::detectCores() - 1}, which helps when instances
are many or \code{solve} is slow and adds overhead on a tiny fit. Last, lower
\code{n_splits} if noisier scores are acceptable. Sequential and parallel runs give
bit-identical results.
}

\section{decide() reports many instances infeasible}{

For those instances \code{solve} found no valid decision, for example a destination
unreachable after closures. The batch still runs; every feasible instance
returns its decision. Read \code{infeasible_reasons(out)}, a tibble of \code{scenario}
and the specific reason, and check that instance's graph, closures, or
capacity. A cut-set that severs every origin-to-destination path is the usual
cause. \code{feasible(out)} holds only the instances that decided;
\code{names(which(!is_feasible(out)))} lists the failing ids.
}

\section{decide() or regret() rejects the scenario as a cost vector}{

The error reads \code{scenario_new} (or \code{scenario_test}) "has a different value in
every row". Passed positionally, a cost vector is easy to put where the
scenario id belongs, and a cost has a distinct value per row, so it groups
nothing into instances. Pass the grouping ids, the same \code{scenario} given to
\code{\link[=dfl_fit]{dfl_fit()}}. The fit path catches this through its modelling-set check; at
\code{\link[=decide]{decide()}} and \code{\link[=regret]{regret()}} the guard reports it directly.
}

\section{The route comes back as row numbers instead of arc ids}{

\code{element_sequence} and \code{selected_elements} show "1" "2" "3". No \code{element_id}
was supplied, so ids defaulted to per-scenario row positions. Supply labels:
\code{element_id} on \code{\link[=dfl_fit]{dfl_fit()}} and \code{element_id_new} on \code{\link[=decide]{decide()}}, or build
inputs with \code{dfl_data(..., element_id = arc_id)}, or use \code{\link[=prepare_instances]{prepare_instances()}},
which sets \code{element_id} to \code{arc_id} automatically.
}

\section{prepare_instances matched only a fraction of the rows}{

This is the coverage report. A row is dropped only when it cannot be placed
(its arc is not in \code{arcs}, its date is not a delivery-day, or that arc was
closed that day). A low matched percentage is the normal shape of sparsely
observed data. Read the printed report and \code{attr(x, "unplaceable")} for
example keys, and fix obvious join typos. Nothing is imputed; every matched
cost still trains the model, and only a few fully covered instances are needed
to score.
}

\section{Decision-focused looks the same as the baseline}{

On this data it may not help, which is a possible result rather than a
malfunction. Read the comparison in \code{summary(fit)} or \code{regret(fit, x_test, cost_test, scenario_test)}; the sign is labelled and lower regret is better.
Read \code{plot(fit, type = "roles")}: if few or no features were rescued, there
was little decision signal to exploit. If few instances were scored, the proxy
had little to learn from, and more fully covered instances may change the
result.
}

\section{All the weight landed on one choice}{

A corner solution is a valid optimum. It can occur when one option dominates,
or when a loose cap or near-identical predicted costs push the answer to a
corner. Inspect the predicted costs with \code{as_tibble(out)} or \code{predict()}, and
the constraint (the \code{max_weight} on \code{\link[=capital_allocation_problem]{capital_allocation_problem()}}, the
knapsack capacity). Tighten the cap if a corner solution is unwanted. \code{\link[=decide]{decide()}}
returns the optimum without smoothing.
}

\section{A different route on re-run}{

Two fits without a fixed seed; \code{seed = NULL} draws a fresh one each fit. The
one random step is how instances are resampled to score features. Fix it up
front with \verb{dfl_control(seed = <integer>)}. To reproduce an earlier fit, feed
its seed back: \code{dfl_control(seed = seed(fit))}. \code{\link[=decide]{decide()}}
itself is deterministic; deciding again from one held fit never changes.
}

\section{A saved fit will not reload, or the .rds is huge}{

A custom \code{solve} captured its enclosing environment (a big data frame or a
database handle), dragging it into the \code{.rds}; a warning fired at fit time.
Built-ins never hit this. Define \code{solve} to read only \code{costs} and \code{instance}
and pass per-instance data inside \code{instance} via \code{\link[=make_instances]{make_instances()}}; such a
\code{solve} saves to a few kilobytes. Or share the data plus \code{seed(fit)} and let a
colleague re-fit, which never serialises the closure.
}

\section{"solve for scenario '...' returned a vector of length m"}{

\code{solve} returned the wrong number of values, or a non-numeric, \code{NA}, or
\code{Inf} vector. The eager probe caught it before any model was fit. Return
exactly one finite number per element row of that instance, in row order (0/1,
or a weight). For grids, fix on row-major or column-major and use it both when
building rows and when flattening the solution, the \code{t()} discipline from
\code{?dflasso-solvers}.
}

\section{Results differ on a colleague's machine}{

A re-fit is bit-identical only on the same R, \pkg{glmnet}, and BLAS. Across
versions the selected-feature list can move by a feature or two near the
margin, which is not an error by either machine. Judge a result by each
feature's \code{proxy_score} and the \code{\link[=regret]{regret()}} comparison rather than the bare
feature list. To remove the variation, reproduce in a pinned environment (the
repository's \code{Dockerfile}, or \code{renv::snapshot()} and \code{renv::restore()}), or
hand over the saved object to reproduce the routes exactly.
}

\section{Two mistakes, but only one shows}{

Structural checks run all at once per phase (structure, then the solver probe,
then coverage), and every check in a phase fires before any model is fit. Read
the whole list (up to about 8 problems with a \verb{(+k more)} tail) and fix them
together in one round-trip.
}

